  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered a violation of the law?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is universally considered a **violation of the law**. It is a serious criminal offense in virtually all countries and is punishable by significant legal penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture.\n\nMoney laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or terrorism) to make it appear as though it comes from legitimate sources. This process typically involves three stages:\n1. **Placement**: Introducing illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the source of the funds through complex transactions.\n3. **Integration**: Making the money appear legitimate by reinvesting it into the economy.\n\nGovernments and international organizations, such as the **United Nations**, **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, and **Interpol**, actively combat money laundering through laws, regulations, and enforcement efforts. Businesses, especially financial institutions, are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities. \n\nCommitting or aiding in money laundering can lead to severe legal consequences.",
